Notwithstanding the foregoing, when the court was initially created, Congress had to resolve which chief judge of the predecessor courts would become the first chief judge. It was decided that the chief judge of the predecessor court who had the most seniority, as chief judge, would be the new chief judge.<ref>{{USPL|97|164}} §166, {{USStat|96|50}}.</ref> This made Howard T. Markey, former chief judge of the Court of Customs and Patent Appeals, the first chief judge.

===Succession of seats===
The court has twelve seats for active judges, numbered in alphabetical order by their occupant at the time the court was formed, with the sole vacant seat being numbered last. Judges who retire into [[senior_status|senior status]] remain on the bench but leave their seat vacant. That seat is filled by the next circuit judge appointed by the [[President_of_the_United_States|President]].

